'''Joseph Paxson Iddings''' (January 21, 1857 – September 8, 1920) was an American [[geologist]] and a [[petrologist]].<ref name="NAP">[http://www.nap.edu/readingroom.php?book=biomems&page=jiddings.html National Academies Press:Biographical Memoirs:Joseph Paxson Iddings, By H. S. Yoder, Jr.]</ref><ref>[http://siarchives.si.edu/collections/siris_arc_217362?back=%2Fcollections%2Fsearch%3Fquery%3D%2522Archives%2522%26facets%3DPP_Geo%26page%3D1%26perpage%3D10%26sort%3Drelevancy%26view%3Dlist Smithsonian Institution Archives;SIA RU007205, Iddings, Joseph Paxson 1857-1920, Joseph Paxson Iddings Papers, 1914]</ref><ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/281721/Joseph-Paxson-Iddings Encyclopædia Britannica:Joseph Paxson Iddings]</ref><ref>[http://bulletin.geoscienceworld.org/content/44/2/352.short Memorial of Joseph Paxton Iddings &#91;1857-1920&#93; Geological Society of America Bulletin, April 1933, v. 44, p. 352-374]</ref> The [[National Academies Press]] called Iddings "an outstanding leader of petrology".<ref name="NAP"/> The [[New York Times]] called him "a distinguished petrologist".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1907/06/27/archives/taft-says-knoxs-handicap-is-gone-conferring-of-yales-degree-of.html?sq=Joseph%2520Paxson%2520Iddings&scp=1&st=cse TAFT SAYS KNOX'S HANDICAP IS GONE; Conferring of Yale's Degree of Doctor of Laws Has Removed It. TALKS AT ALUMNI DINNER Says He and Knox Are Like Man Riding Away from Office, but Going Very Slowly. June 27, 1907, ]</ref> Iddings was a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]],<ref name="NAP"/> a member of the [[Geological Society of London]],<ref name="NAP"/> the [[American Philosophical Society]],<ref name="NAP"/> a fellow of the [[Geological Society of America]],<ref name="NAP"/> a member of the Scientific Society of Christiania,<ref name="NAP"/> an honorary member of the Société française de Mineralogie,<ref name="NAP"/> an honorary curator of petrology in the U.S. National Museum.<ref name="NAP"/> [[Yale University]] established Iddings Scholarship for Graduate Studies.<ref name="NAP"/>
The mineral [[iddingsite]] was named after him.<ref>[https://www.mindat.org/min-7006.html Iddingsite on Mindat.org]</ref>
